    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="230"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d230">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">700.00116 M.E./113a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Amtorg Trading Corporation</gloss>, New York, N.
                        Y.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-02">March 2,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sirs</hi>: Your attention is invited to the enclosed
                        documents<note n="65" xml:id="d230fn65">None attached to file copy of this
                        document. The enclosures were statements issued by the Army and Navy
                        Munitions Board dated October 11, 1939, and January 19, 1940, <ref
                            target="frus1939v01#pg_855">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1939, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 855</ref>, and <ref
                            target="frus1940v02#pg_252">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1940, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                            p. 252</ref>, respectively; the President’s statement of December 2,
                        1939, Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, December 16,
                        1939, p. 686; and the Department of State’s press release of December 15,
                        1939, <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 685.</note> in regard to the policy
                    of this Government in respect to the exportation of airplanes, aeronautical
                    equipment, and materials essential to airplane manufacture to countries the
                    armed forces of which are engaged in unprovoked bombing and machine-gunning of
                    civilian populations from the air, and in regard to the exportation of certain
                    listed commodities essential to the national defense.</p>
                <p>In view of the fact that your company is an American corporation incorporated
                    under the laws of New York, it is assumed and expected that you will wish to
                    abide by the policies of this Government set forth in the enclosed documents. I
                    should appreciate it if you would inform me that the Department is correct in
                    this assumption and in this expectation.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph</hi> C. <hi rend="smallcaps">Green</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
